Tekmira also worked on providing liposomal delivery technology to other companies. In 2007 it signed a license agreement with Alnylam Pharmaceuticals so that Alynylam could use it to deliver its own RNAi drugs; that deal was expanded into a manufacturing agreement in 2009.[9]
Most of those products not focused on viral diseases faltered,[10] and Tekmira had only $6.3 million in cash when it filed suit against Alnylam in 2011 for breaching its contract and stealing trade secrets.[9] The suit was settled in 2012, with Alylylam agreeing to pay Tekmira $65 million in termination fees, and the companies negotiated a new license agreement with lower milestones and royalties, which covers Alynylam's product patisiran.[9][11]
